      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Network infrastructure considerations for Site Recovery",
      "pos": [
        540,
        595
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Azure Site Recovery service contributes to a robust business continuity and disaster recovery (BCDR) solution by protecting and recovering your on-premises physical servers and virtual machines with orchestration and automation of replication and failover to Azure, or to a secondary on-premises datacenter.",
      "pos": [
        597,
        908
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This article is aimed at the virtualization team responsible for architecting, implementing, and supporting a BCDR solution and infrastructure that includes System Center VMM and Azure Site Recovery.",
      "pos": [
        911,
        1110
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Overview",
      "pos": [
        1115,
        1123
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The purpose of your BCDR strategy is to keep your business applications running, and to  restore failed workloads and services so the organization can quickly resume normal operations.",
      "pos": [
        1125,
        1309
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Developing disaster recovery strategies is challenging, due inherent difficulty of predicting unforeseen events, and the high cost of implementing adequate protection against far-reaching failures.",
      "pos": [
        1310,
        1507
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Site Recovery helps you implement protection and failover from your primary data center to a secondary data center (or to Azure) by initially copying (replicating) your primary data, and then periodically refreshing the replicas.",
      "pos": [
        1508,
        1743
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a crucial part of your BCDR planning you need to define your Recovery Time Objective (RTO) and Recovery Point Objective (RPO) so that can you get your organization data back online as quickly as possible (with a low RTO) and with minimum data loss (low RPO).",
      "pos": [
        1745,
        2006
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The network design in your organization is a potential bottleneck to your RTO and RPO objectives and solid design planning can help avoid this bottleneck.",
      "pos": [
        2007,
        2161
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you've decided to use the Azure Site Recovery service to help implement protection and failover there are a couple of key issues in network design for BCDR:",
      "pos": [
        2165,
        2324
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>VMM design<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: I'm using System Center VMM.",
      "pos": [
        2328,
        2372
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How should I handle the network design to integrate VMM and Site Recover?",
      "pos": [
        2373,
        2446
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Connectivity after failover<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: I'm using Site Recovery to run a failover.",
      "pos": [
        2449,
        2524
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How can I make sure my applications and workloads are available and reachable after failover completes?",
      "pos": [
        2525,
        2628
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VMM design",
      "pos": [
        2633,
        2643
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can layer Site Recovery on top of your existing VMM design, regardless of whether that design uses a single or multiple VMM servers.",
      "pos": [
        2645,
        2781
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Standalone VMM server",
      "pos": [
        2788,
        2809
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this topology, you'll deploy a VMM server on a virtual machine in the primary site, and then replicate this virtual machine to a secondary site with Site Recovery and Hyper-V Replica.",
      "pos": [
        2811,
        2997
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You might consider installing the VMM sever and its supporting SQL Server on the same virtual machine can reduce downtime, because only one VM has to be instantiated.",
      "pos": [
        2998,
        3164
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the VMM service is using a remote SQL Server you'll need to recover the SQL Server instance before recovering the VMM server.",
      "pos": [
        3165,
        3295
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To deploy a single VMM on a VM with Hyper-V Replica:",
      "pos": [
        3298,
        3350
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Set up the VMM on a VM with SQL Server installed.",
      "pos": [
        3355,
        3404
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Add the hosts to be managed to clouds on this VMM server.",
      "pos": [
        3408,
        3465
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Log in to the Azure portal and then configure clouds for protection.",
      "pos": [
        3469,
        3537
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Enable replication for all the VMs that need to be protected by the VMM server.",
      "pos": [
        3541,
        3620
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Go to the Hyper-V Manager console, choose Hyper-V Replica, and then enable replication on the VMM VM.",
      "pos": [
        3624,
        3725
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Ensure that the VMM VM is not added to the clouds that are protected by ASR service so that the Hyper-V Replication settings are not overridden by ASR.",
      "pos": [
        3729,
        3880
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the event of a disaster, workloads can be recovered as follows:",
      "pos": [
        3882,
        3948
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Fail over the replica VMM VM to the recovery site, using Hyper-V Manager.",
      "pos": [
        3953,
        4026
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the VMM VM has been recovered, the user can login to the Hyper-V Recovery Manager from the secondary site.",
      "pos": [
        4030,
        4142
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "After the unplanned failover is complete, the user can access all the resources at the primary site.",
      "pos": [
        4146,
        4246
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that the VMM VM will need to be failed over manually to the secondary site before workloads can be failed over.",
      "pos": [
        4250,
        4366
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Clustered VMM server",
      "pos": [
        4374,
        4394
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Deploying VMM in a cluster<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/gg610675.aspx)</ept> provides high availability and protection against hardware failover.",
      "pos": [
        4397,
        4553
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you're deploying your VMM cluster with Site Recovery note that:",
      "pos": [
        4554,
        4620
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The VMM server should be deployed in a stretched cluster across geographically separate sites.",
      "pos": [
        4622,
        4716
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The SQL Server database used by VMM should be protected with SQL Server AlwaysOn availability groups with a replica on the secondary site.",
      "pos": [
        4717,
        4855
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If disaster occurs the VMM server and its corresponding SQL Server will automatically fail over to the recovery site.",
      "pos": [
        4856,
        4973
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can then fail over workloads using Site Recovery.",
      "pos": [
        4974,
        5027
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Stretched VMM cluster",
      "pos": [
        5031,
        5052
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Connectivity after failover",
      "pos": [
        5119,
        5146
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Modern applications are almost always dependent on networking to some degree, so physically moving a service from one site to another represents a networking challenge to make sure applications and workloads are reachable after failover.",
      "pos": [
        5148,
        5385
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are two main solutions to this issue:",
      "pos": [
        5386,
        5429
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Fixed IP addresses<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: The first approach is to maintain fixed IP addresses.",
      "pos": [
        5433,
        5510
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Despite the services moving and the hosting servers being in different physical locations, applications take the IP address configuration with them to the new location.",
      "pos": [
        5511,
        5679
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        5682,
        5808
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Modified IP addresses<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: The second approach requires changing the IP address during the transition into the recovered site."
    },
    {
      "content": "Option 1: Fixed IP addresses",
      "pos": [
        5815,
        5843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "From a disaster recovery perspective, using fixed IP addresses appears to be the easiest method to implement.",
      "pos": [
        5845,
        5954
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However there are a number of potential challenges which in practice make it the least popular approach.",
      "pos": [
        5955,
        6059
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure Site Recovery provides the capability to retain the IP addresses in all scenarios.",
      "pos": [
        6060,
        6148
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Before you decide to take this approach let's look at the considerations for the main scenarios (stretched subnet and subnet failover).",
      "pos": [
        6149,
        6284
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Stretched subnet",
      "pos": [
        6292,
        6308
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a stretched subnet the subnet is available simultaneously in both the primary and target locations.",
      "pos": [
        6310,
        6412
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In simple terms this means you can move a server and its IP (Layer 3) configuration to the secondary site, and the network will route traffic to the new location automatically.",
      "pos": [
        6413,
        6589
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is trivial to deal with from a server perspective but it has a number of challenges:",
      "pos": [
        6590,
        6679
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "From a Layer 2 (data link layer) perspective it requires networking equipment that can manage a stretched VLAN, although this type of equipment is now widely available.",
      "pos": [
        6685,
        6853
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The second and more difficult problem is that by stretching the VLAN the potential fault domain extends to both sites, essentially becoming a single point of failure.",
      "pos": [
        6856,
        7022
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Although unlikely it could happen that a broadcast storm starts and cannot be isolated.",
      "pos": [
        7023,
        7110
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We've seen mixed opinions about this issue, that range from successful implementation to “never”.",
      "pos": [
        7111,
        7208
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A stretched subnet isn't possible if you're failing over to Azure as your DR site.",
      "pos": [
        7211,
        7293
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Subnet Failover",
      "pos": [
        7300,
        7315
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It's possible to implement subnet failover in order to obtain the benefits of a stretched subnet without actually stretching it.",
      "pos": [
        7317,
        7445
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this configuration any given subnet is present at Site 1 or Site 2, but never at both sites simultaneously.",
      "pos": [
        7446,
        7556
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To maintain the IP address space in the event of a failover, you can programmatically arrange for the router infrastructure to move the subnets from one site to another.",
      "pos": [
        7557,
        7726
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a failover scenario the subnets move with their associated protected VMs.",
      "pos": [
        7727,
        7803
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The main drawback to this approach is that in the event of a failure you have to move the whole subnet, which might be a reasonable solution, but could affect failover granularity considerations.",
      "pos": [
        7805,
        8000
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Let’s take a look at how a fictional enterprise (Contoso) is able to replicate its VMs to a recovery location, while failing over the entire subnet.",
      "pos": [
        8003,
        8151
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We'll look at how Contoso is able to manages its subnets while replicating VMs between two on-premises locations, and discuss how subnet failover works when Azure is used as the disaster recovery site.",
      "pos": [
        8152,
        8353
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example - Subnet failover in an enterprise",
      "pos": [
        8361,
        8403
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The primary site has applications running in subnet 192.168.1.0/24.",
      "pos": [
        8408,
        8475
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The entire subnet will fail over, and all the virtual machines in the subnet will be failed over to the recovery site and retain their IP addresses",
      "pos": [
        8478,
        8625
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As shown in the diagram below the routes between primary site and recovery site, third site and primary site, and third site and recovery site will have to be appropriately modified to reflect the fact that all the virtual machines belonging to subnet 192.168.1.0/24 have been moved to the recovery site.",
      "pos": [
        8628,
        8932
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This diagram assumes that:",
      "pos": [
        8935,
        8961
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each data center is serviced by its own instance of VMM.",
      "pos": [
        8969,
        9025
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There will be no replication of the System Center VMM databases between datacenters.",
      "pos": [
        9026,
        9110
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each data center uses static IP addresses for the virtual machines.",
      "pos": [
        9118,
        9185
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Connectivity between the data centers is via a dedicated circuit and not via VPN connectivity over the internet.",
      "pos": [
        9193,
        9305
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Before failover",
      "pos": [
        9309,
